Not sausage!

00:03:09.064 --> 00:03:10.899 position:50% align:center
[stomachs growling]

00:03:10.982 --> 00:03:12.233 position:50% align:center
[HORIGUCHI laughs]

00:03:12.317 --> 00:03:14.652 position:50% align:center
Let's take a little break,
shall we?

00:03:14.736 --> 00:03:16.613 position:50% align:center
[TOMORI] Hey, would you listen
to this, you guys?

00:03:16.696 --> 00:03:19.866 position:50% align:center
It says, "Whereas an asteroid's
reflectance spectrum is derived

00:03:19.949 --> 00:03:22.410 position:50% align:center
from ordinary
chondrite in S- types.

00:03:22.494 --> 00:03:25.622 position:50% align:center
It's derived from carbonaceous
chondrite in C-types.

00:03:25.705 --> 00:03:27.165 position:50% align:center
What's that even mean?

00:03:27.248 --> 00:03:29.959 position:50% align:center
Basically, when you
analyze an asteroid's light,

00:03:30.043 --> 00:03:32.629 position:50% align:center
you can identify its
general composition.

00:03:32.712 --> 00:03:35.090 position:50% align:center
Wow. So, you mean,
there are actually different

00:03:35.173 --> 00:03:36.675 position:50% align:center
types of asteroids?

00:03:36.758 --> 00:03:38.677 position:50% align:center
For example,
the asteroid Hayabusa

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:41.221 position:50% align:center
was launched at was
the S-type, Itokawa.

00:03:41.304 --> 00:03:43.598 position:50% align:center
Whereas, the one
Hayabusa 2 was launched at

00:03:43.682 --> 00:03:45.809 position:50% align:center
was a carbonaceous C- type.

00:03:45.892 --> 00:03:47.560 position:50% align:center
The thing is, unlike planetoids,

00:03:47.644 --> 00:03:50.855 position:50% align:center
most asteroids out there haven't
gone through thermal evolution.

00:03:50.939 --> 00:03:52.232 position:50% align:center
[TOMORI] Meaning they're
the same as they were

00:03:52.315 --> 00:03:55.485 position:50% align:center
a long time ago?
Kinda like unbaked cookie dough?

00:03:55.568 --> 00:03:57.779 position:50% align:center
Right! That's why,
if we study the rocks

00:03:57.862 --> 00:04:00.031 position:50% align:center
that come from asteroids,
we can trace the history

00:04:00.115 --> 00:04:01.866 position:50% align:center
of our solar system.

00:04:01.950 --> 00:04:04.119 position:50% align:center
Yeah, I see.

00:04:04.202 --> 00:04:08.164 position:50% align:center
[MIRA] So, people go to space
and bring back rocks, huh? Nice.

00:04:08.248 --> 00:04:11.960 position:50% align:center
Sounds like a joint project
for astronomers and geologists.

00:04:12.043 --> 00:04:14.004 position:50% align:center
You're in the
Earth Sciences Club, right?

00:04:14.087 --> 00:04:16.047 position:50% align:center
Why did it get split up, anyway?

00:04:16.131 --> 00:04:17.632 position:50% align:center
[AO]
Well...

00:04:17.716 --> 00:04:20.468 position:50% align:center
It was two different
clubs, originally.

00:04:20.552 --> 00:04:23.430 position:50% align:center
[TOMORI] Hmm. I guess it's true
that there are a lot of fields

00:04:23.513 --> 00:04:25.682 position:50% align:center
lumped into the Earth Sciences.

00:04:25.765 --> 00:04:27.684 position:50% align:center
Being the science
of the Earth and all.

00:04:27.767 --> 00:04:30.520 position:50% align:center
 Some people call it
"geological sciences," too.

00:04:30.603 --> 00:04:32.063 position:50% align:center
"Geoscience" for short.

00:04:32.147 --> 00:04:33.481 position:50% align:center
Geoscience.

00:04:33.565 --> 00:04:35.066 position:50% align:center
[AO]
Huh?

00:04:35.150 --> 00:04:37.569 position:50% align:center
[MIRA, AO]
Geoscience Club.

00:04:39.529 --> 00:04:41.114 position:50% align:center
This should be all
the reading we'll need to do

00:04:41.197 --> 00:04:43.533 position:50% align:center
to prep for tomorrow's
presentation.

00:04:43.616 --> 00:04:45.910 position:50% align:center
All right! I guess
the only thing left to do

00:04:45.994 --> 00:04:49.372 position:50% align:center
is hope tonight's
observation goes well!

00:04:49.456 --> 00:04:51.666 position:50% align:center
Looks like the
weather's gonna cooperate.

00:04:59.424 --> 00:05:01.509 position:50% align:center
[ENDOU]
Thanks, Hanashima, Horiguchi.

00:05:01.593 --> 00:05:03.094 position:50% align:center
Take good care of them, okay?

00:05:03.178 --> 00:05:04.596 position:50% align:center
[HORIGUCHI, HANASHIMA]
Sure.

00:05:04.679 --> 00:05:06.514 position:50% align:center
Well, good luck, you guys!

00:05:06.598 --> 00:05:08.683 position:50% align:center
Don't forget. Have fun, too!

00:05:08.767 --> 00:05:10.643 position:50% align:center
[GIRLS]
Thanks!

00:05:10.727 --> 00:05:12.896 position:50% align:center
Okay, now we'll
start photographing.

00:05:12.979 --> 00:05:14.856 position:50% align:center
This'll take
a little time, though.

00:05:14.939 --> 00:05:17.067 position:50% align:center
So, why don't you all
go outside and take a look

00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:18.735 position:50% align:center
