don't know yet.

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:47.365 position:50% align:center
All I really care about
is getting to discover

00:06:47.449 --> 00:06:49.868 position:50% align:center
an asteroid and name it Ao.

00:06:49.951 --> 00:06:52.245 position:50% align:center
If we're able to
make that dream come true,

00:06:52.328 --> 00:06:54.914 position:50% align:center
then maybe I'll finally be
ready to focus on finding

00:06:54.998 --> 00:06:57.042 position:50% align:center
a new dream to take its place.

00:06:57.125 --> 00:06:58.209 position:50% align:center
[AO chuckles]

00:06:58.293 --> 00:06:59.961 position:50% align:center
Yeah. I get it.

00:07:00.045 --> 00:07:02.255 position:50% align:center
You're taking it
all one day at a time!

00:07:02.339 --> 00:07:03.548 position:50% align:center
That's great.

00:07:03.631 --> 00:07:05.133 position:50% align:center
That doesn't surprise me.

00:07:05.216 --> 00:07:07.510 position:50% align:center
You both do seem
to live in the present.

00:07:07.594 --> 00:07:09.095 position:50% align:center
[MIRA, AO]
Yeah.

00:07:09.179 --> 00:07:10.889 position:50% align:center
We'll do our best to find one.

00:07:10.972 --> 00:07:12.432 position:50% align:center
It would feel really
good to help you two

00:07:12.515 --> 00:07:15.268 position:50% align:center
achieve your dream, after all!

00:07:15.352 --> 00:07:16.936 position:50% align:center
Totally agree!

00:07:18.605 --> 00:07:22.442 position:50% align:center
[MIRA, AO] We've done it.
We've finally made it this far!

00:07:25.362 --> 00:07:27.989 position:50% align:center
[HANASHIMA] All right, the first
round of photographs is done.

00:07:28.073 --> 00:07:30.909 position:50% align:center
And let's do our best to
cover yesterday's share, too.

00:07:30.992 --> 00:07:32.660 position:50% align:center
[GIRLS]
Right!

00:07:33.745 --> 00:07:35.914 position:50% align:center
There are even more
stars than last night.

00:07:35.997 --> 00:07:37.499 position:50% align:center
[TOMORI]
Yeah.

00:07:38.667 --> 00:07:43.380 position:50% align:center
[AO] Aw... Doesn't look like
there are any new ones.

00:07:43.463 --> 00:07:45.173 position:50% align:center
Send me the data, too, would ya?

00:07:45.256 --> 00:07:47.008 position:50% align:center
I'll do a quick double-check.

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:12.659 position:50% align:center
[MAKITA]
How about this region, here?

00:08:12.742 --> 00:08:15.203 position:50% align:center
[TOMORI]
Nope, nothing.

00:08:15.286 --> 00:08:17.747 position:50% align:center
[MIRA]
I can only see known ones here.

00:08:17.831 --> 00:08:19.249 position:50% align:center
[HANASHIMA]
Conditions aren't bad tonight,

00:08:19.332 --> 00:08:21.835 position:50% align:center
so it all depends on
your luck and tenacity.

00:08:21.918 --> 00:08:23.503 position:50% align:center
[MIRA]
Luck, huh?

00:08:23.586 --> 00:08:27.507 position:50% align:center
Asteroids are always rotating.
And so many are misshapen.

00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:29.509 position:50% align:center
So, they can suddenly
appear to be brighter

00:08:29.592 --> 00:08:31.052 position:50% align:center
depending on the angle.

00:08:31.136 --> 00:08:32.387 position:50% align:center
Mira! Look, there!

00:08:32.470 --> 00:08:34.055 position:50% align:center
It's moving!

00:08:34.139 --> 00:08:35.974 position:50% align:center
[MAKITA gasps]
Which one?

00:08:36.057 --> 00:08:37.434 position:50% align:center
That one.

00:08:37.517 --> 00:08:38.852 position:50% align:center
Yeah, you're right.

00:08:38.935 --> 00:08:40.812 position:50% align:center
The image is unclear,
so the auto-discovery program

00:08:40.895 --> 00:08:42.105 position:50% align:center
isn't reading it.

00:08:42.188 --> 00:08:43.523 position:50% align:center
There's also a chance
that it could just

00:08:43.606 --> 00:08:45.066 position:50% align:center
be noise, too, right?

00:08:45.150 --> 00:08:47.527 position:50% align:center
[HORIGUCHI] Hanashima, just to
be sure, could you try updating

00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:50.321 position:50% align:center
our database of
known astrological objects?

00:08:50.405 --> 00:08:51.531 position:50% align:center
[HANASHIMA]
Right, yeah.

00:08:53.783 --> 00:08:55.368 position:50% align:center
[MIRA]
Ao.

00:08:55.452 --> 00:08:57.912 position:50% align:center
Okay, then, what would you like?

00:08:57.996 --> 00:09:00.081 position:50% align:center
Shall we photograph
the same region once more

00:09:00.165 --> 00:09:04.002 position:50% align:center
