feels so lame.

00:10:26.835 --> 00:10:29.713 position:50% align:center
I know, but we
still need to do the work.

00:10:29.796 --> 00:10:31.798 position:50% align:center
Yes, it's important
to write your report.

00:10:31.881 --> 00:10:34.217 position:50% align:center
Even if it didn't produce
the results you hoped for.

00:10:34.300 --> 00:10:35.635 position:50% align:center
[AO, MIRA]
Huh?

00:10:35.719 --> 00:10:37.095 position:50% align:center
[HANASHIMA]
The record of your experience is

00:10:37.178 --> 00:10:40.557 position:50% align:center
precious information for
anyone observing after you.

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:41.725 position:50% align:center
[AO, MIRA gasp]

00:10:41.808 --> 00:10:43.727 position:50% align:center
You know. The same way
you all referenced

00:10:43.810 --> 00:10:46.396 position:50% align:center
past research documentation
for this project.

00:10:46.479 --> 00:10:50.150 position:50% align:center
That's right!
Thank you, all who came before!

00:10:50.233 --> 00:10:52.027 position:50% align:center
Kind of exciting, isn't it?

00:10:52.110 --> 00:10:53.236 position:50% align:center
Yeah.

00:10:59.325 --> 00:11:00.994 position:50% align:center
[MIRA] I think this works
for our explanation

00:11:01.077 --> 00:11:03.121 position:50% align:center
of the telescope.

00:11:03.204 --> 00:11:05.040 position:50% align:center
Yeah, I agree.

00:11:05.123 --> 00:11:08.418 position:50% align:center
Oh, I actually have
a picture of the Murikabushi.

00:11:08.501 --> 00:11:09.669 position:50% align:center
That would be great!

00:11:09.753 --> 00:11:12.130 position:50% align:center
